<font color="#FF0000"> DIALOGUE LEADING TO HEALING</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 17 17:51:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Mustang Two Four;<br>
Love the sound of chopper blades. Except, when I though they were coming in to get us out of a tough spot. Picked up my gear and was ready to make a run for them when they landed in the paddies. Couldn't understand why they landed out in the open. Though they were going to get creamed. But, all they brought in was a bunch of ugly, dirty screaming Marines coming to our rescue. none the less, I could have kissed them all that night, and I did forgive the chopper pilot for not taking us out. I was just glad I didn't have to stand watch that night. Gosh, the simple bennies, we accepted after getting all shot up and losing 3/4th of our platoon  (what we appreciated, was not having to stand watch that night). <br><br>
Spatz, you little commie, what gives?  I don't know what Ed said to you, guess I will have to go back and re-read what you two were talking about. He didn't promise you a nice rich fancy secret name did he? Or, a Vietnam Vet decoder ring? Did PBS &amp; CNN call you for an interview? Is this the new improved version? <br><br>
To Tom:<br>
Why go to Nam; come visit Little Saigon, in Orange county, California. 96,000 population all within a few square miles. But I couldn't find a map of Vietnam there, no where. Did buy some furniture. When it broke I was trying to return it, but they refused to take it back, until they saw what SILENT WARRIOR talks about. <br>
The VN Cross of Gallantry with Valor device and palm on my CAP. Hate to wear that thing, makes me feel like some of those old WWII gizzards, that hang out at the VFW watering hole and swap war stories. <br>
But the manager, once he saw those ribbons, came and set up the new furniture in my home without any further problem. I never knew what that medal was good for until then (actually, I just asked him what his nationality was, and when he found out I was a Marine that had served in Nam, caused him much pain, lost face before everyone, bowed and thanked me over and over again. Repented before his store full of employees and all). I was going to show them the Vietnamese Civil Service Ribbon, but was afraid he would take us to his house for dinner with that one. <br>
At the PX set up at the reunion, the guy behind the desk (must have been Air Force), did not find it amusing when I asked him to add one of those funny looking blue and white air medals to the string of ribbons he was putting together for me. Told him I liked the color and figured I would get the good stuff, unlike the frayed ones the guy that hangs out with the &quot;homeless will work for food&quot; sign wears that he bought at the Army surplus store. PX guy couldn't take a joke. I Figured I spend enough times jumping in and out of those choppers to have earned one. <br><br>
Poor Sgt. Stanford thought the ships rivets were falling apart, saw all those metal chips popping off the ships sides, didn't realize the new vented holes were being made from incoming rounds making their way through and through. I was as glad to get out as the pilot was in unloading us.<br><br>
To Silent Warrior,<br>
I too have come to the conclusion concerning the northern warriors, many I realized even the tall Chinese that had not fired his weapon did not want to be there. They had been forced to take arms and did so. Some were very dedicated others looked for an opportunity to turn defect. We even had two Marines leave (walk off) Liberty Bridge, one to fight them all alone, the other to join the other side. I pitied the defectors that turned themselves over to us, because I knew some would not survive once we turned them over to the South Vietnamese government. <br>
Like major Lum, NVA soldier, he was known as the Robin Hood of Dai Loc, when we destroyed the rice field and hooches by napalm and artillery, he tookhis people into the vills and rebuilt them for the local villagers. Like Spatz, you didn't know if you wanted to admire him for his dedication, or shoot him because he was out to win them over with kind words, deeds and honey. <br>
Major Lum,fell into one of our ambushed sites, got gut shot and would have made it. Spoke perfect English had gone to Stanford for a couple of years. But by the time our intelligence officers got to him in was dead at the hands of ARVN's who did not realize the value of the man.<br><br>

<p><code>-- SparrowHawk,   (Cook Barela) </code><p>


